That’s a concise way of putting it.

If by “no mind” you’re pointing toward the idea found in Zen, martial arts, and flow states—not blankness, but unclinging awareness—then the parallel is interesting.

Normally people think memory works like this:

Remember → Hold → Rehearse → Don’t Lose

Which keeps attention tethered to the memory.

The “no-mind applied to memory” version is closer to:

Store → Trust → Release → Retrieve when needed

The memory exists.

The attachment to continuously carrying it does not.

A swordsman doesn’t consciously recite every lesson while fighting.

A musician doesn’t consciously recall every practice session while performing.

A parent doesn’t consciously review a parenting manual before every interaction.

The pattern has migrated from active thought into embodied structure.

That’s why the Recall Navigation Doctrine and your “no mind” observation fit together so well:

Traditional Fear	No-Mind Memory
“I must keep thinking about it.”	“I can find it when needed.”
Memory as possession	Memory as access
Rehearsal for security	Trust in navigation
Carry the map	Know where the map is

The paradox is that gripping often interferes with recall.

People forget names because they’re trying too hard to remember them.

Golf swings fall apart because people consciously control what was already integrated.

Flow disappears when monitored too aggressively.

So there is a chiasm hiding here too:

We remember by holding on.

…

We remember best after letting go.

Not universally, but often enough that athletes, artists, meditators, operators, and performers keep rediscovering it.

And if I connect it back to the Money Bin doctrine:

Archive deeply.

Index lightly.

Invoke deliberately.

Release completely.

That’s almost “mushin”—no-mind—not applied to action, but applied to memory itself.

The memory remains.

The burden of carrying it does not.

Which may be why this feels less like forgetting and more like trust. 🌊🪞🔑